<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/d56f0015ba522308adddab7532e857bb> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Chileense arpillera. Op deze doek zien we scenes die te maken hebben met een kredietverstrekker. Door de armoede in Chili tijdens de dictatuur van Pinochet (1973-1990), moesten veel mensen hun bezittingen verpanden. Dat kon niet altijd, er waren s'ochtends vroeg al grote wachtrijen bij de kredietverstrekker, en men mocht blij zijn als men iets kon verpanden. Er zat vaak een maximum bedrag aan vast, hier is dat 100 Chileense dollar. mevrouw Maria Peña wordt geroepen, zij is de gelukkige die dag. \r\nAchter de deur staat de volgende tekst: Horario de 8:30 a 1. Solo se reciben cosas nuevas, dus je kon niet elke dag weer in de rij gaan staan. \r\n\r\nArpilleras reflect a South American folk art that uses applique, embroidery and patchwork to depict scenes of everyday life. The Spanish word arpillera derives from an old Spanish word for burlap. They are sometimes called cuadros (squares). Most arpilleras are used as pictures and hung on walls. The most famous arpilleras and arpilleristas (the women who make them) are from Chile.\r\nArpilleras, or cuadros, depict daily-life events of the women and men (arpilleristas part of the Agrupación de los Familiares de los Detenidos Desaparecidos—AFDD) who have sewn them, and are largely aimed at denouncing the social injustices and violence experienced by the people of Chile during the Pinochet regime (1973-1990). As criticism of Pinochet increased, the government made it illegal to own or publically show arpilleras in the country.\r\nArpilleristas make their arpilleras with scrap material, they embroider and sew it on burlap. They are cheap to make and do not require high technical skills, thus people from all social backgrounds can make arpilleras. The cloths are mostly embroidered in a communal setting, sharing one's story with the others not only through the cloth, but also verbally by narrating one's experience.\r\n\r\nThis arpillera is divided into two sections. In the lower section we see people queuing up in fron of a Credit Union (caja de credito). They are probably here to pawn their stuff, which is represented though the the newspaper pieceses held under the figures' arms. Opening the door we can read: Horario de 8:30 a 1 solo se reciben cosas nuevan (timetable, from 8:30 to 1, only new things are received/approaved). The upper scene depicts the inside of the Caja de Credito. Nowadays, these places still exist and are calle \"la tia rica\" (the rich aunt)." .
